(Fig. 3
                        a) shows the optimization of incubation time revealing that at 448 nm the fluorescence of DAC decreased rapidly in the presence of MLT till 55sec after that the decline was slow till 100 sec. Again, the continuous decrease was observed within time period of 100––120 sec and the fluorescence response reached equalities after 2 min. As the time increased from 0 to 2 min, the fluorescence intensity of the sensor device fell significantly. The optimal detection time is certain as 2 min (Fig. 3a). Time-dependent fluorescence response revealed the photostability on irradiation of DAC solution for one hr resulted in 3% decrease in fluorescence intensity Fig. 3b). Moreover, DAC showed high stability of aqueous sodium chloride solution (0–140 µM) as is obvious from the study of fluorescence intensity that remained unchanged (Fig. 3c) and is important for their sensing applications in high-salt environments. Selective detection of MLT relative to some other analogous analytes like serotonin, dopamine, urea, trypsin, sodium chloride (NaCl), glucose, calcium ion, potassium ion was evaluated by fluorescence spectroscopy investigating the quenching efficiency by maintaining the concentrations of all these analytes comparable to that of MLT added in the DAC solution. As shown in the (Fig. 4
                        ) significant changes were observed for all the above-mentioned analytes except serotonin that is exhibiting modest change. This approves that the developed fluorescence sensing system is highly selective towards MLT.
